name: 3-bromo-2-methoxy-6-methyl-benzoic acid
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2433
Reason: The melting point of a compound depends on various intermolecular forces such as hydrogen bonding, dipole-dipole interactions and London dispersion forces. For estimating the melting point of a substituted aromatic compound like 3-bromo-2-methoxy-6-methyl-benzoic acid, we must consider the basic structure and the effect of substituents. The basic unit we'll consider here is benzoic acid, which has a melting point of 122°C. Each substituent will either increase or decrease this value based on its own properties. The bromine atom is a heavy halogen and introduces significant London dispersion forces, which typically raises the melting point. We can estimate this addition to benzoic acid's melting point to be around +20°C. The methoxy group (-OCH3) is slightly electron-donating and can disrupt the planarity and the strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding of the carboxylic acid group, causing the melting point to lower. We can estimate this effect to be around -5°C. The methyl group is electron-donating and can add to the dispersion forces, but to a lesser extent than the bromine. It may also contribute to a slight steric hindrance which could decrease the melting point. We can estimate the effect of the methyl group to be around +5°C. Summing up the contributions, the Prediction for the melting point of 3-bromo-2-methoxy-6-methyl-benzoic acid would be 122 (basic unit) + 20 (Br) - 5 (OCH3) + 5 (CH3) = 142°C.
